Lateral view
(
Fig. 2
). Body dorsally smooth except for two tiny dorsal tubercles on the head, near the eyes (see also dorsal view 
Fig. 2
). Eyes present. Pereonite 1 fused with head, suture present. Pereonites 2, 3 and 4 with anterolateral projections, especially developed in pereonite 2. Pereonite 5 the longest. Pereonite 7 the shortest.

Similar to male except for following characteristics: head and body smooth lacking dorsal or anterolateral projections; presence of oostegites on pereonites 3 and 4, oostegites setose on pereonite 3 (
Fig. 2
); flagellum of antenna 1 with 4 articles; gnathopod 2 basis and ischium lacking distal projection, palm of propodus less setose than in male; pereopods 6 and 7 six-articulate, merus, carpus and propodus with a row of ventral setae, propodus with a proximal grasping spine, dactylus curved.
